Find the greatest common divisor of $40304$ and $30203$.
inference:
To find the greatest common divisor (GCD) of 40304 and 30203, we use the Euclidean algorithm.

Divide 40304 by 30203:
$$40304 = 1 \times 30203 + 10101$$
Now divide 30203 by 10101:
$$30203 = 2 \times 10101 + 10001$$
Now divide 10101 by 10001:
$$10101 = 1 \times 10001 + 100$$
Now divide 10001 by 100:
$$10001 = 100 \times 100 + 1$$
Now divide 100 by 1:
$$100 = 100 \times 1 + 0$$
The last non-zero remainder is 1.

Final Answer: $\boxed{1}$. I hope it is correct.
ground_truth:
By the Euclidean Algorithm: \begin{align*}
\text{gcd}(40304, 30203) &= \text{gcd}(40304-30203, 30203) \\
&= \text{gcd}(10101, 30203) \\
&= \text{gcd}(30203-2\cdot10101, 10101) \\
&= \text{gcd}(10001, 10101) \\
&= \text{gcd}(10101 - 10001, 10001) \\
&= \text{gcd}(100, 10001) \\
&= \text{gcd}(10001 - 100\cdot100, 100) \\
&= \text{gcd}(1, 100) \\
\end{align*}Therefore, the greatest common divisor of $40304$ and $30203$ is $\boxed{1}$
